04376nam a22006735i 9780271083025DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212018pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710830257 a10.1515/97802710830252doi  a(DE-B1597)584377  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBF1618.A7bM3513 2019 7aLAN0150002bisacsh04a133.4/32231 aPender, Kelly, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeing at Genetic Risk :bToward a Rhetoric of Care /cKelly Pender. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource (184 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRSA Series in Transdisciplinary Rhetoric ;v1000tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1 Following Mol's Lead: From Diabetes to BRCA Risk -- t2 From Ideology to Governmentality: A Constructivist View of Genetic Risk -- t3 Making Risk Real: A Praxiographic Inquiry into Being BRCA+ -- t4 Toward a Rhetoric of Care for the At Risk -- tConclusion: Invention in RSTM: Another Moderate Response to the Two-World Problem -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRhetorics of choice have dominated the biosocial discourses surrounding BRCA risk for decades, telling women at genetic risk for breast and ovarian cancers that they are free to choose how (and whether) to deal with their risk. Critics argue that women at genetic risk are, in fact, not free to choose but rather are forced to make particular choices. In Being at Genetic Risk, Kelly Pender argues for a change in the conversation around genetic risk that focuses less on choice and more on care.Being at Genetic Risk offers a new set of conceptual starting points for understanding what is at stake with a BRCA diagnosis and what the focus on choice obstructs from view. Through a praxiographic reading of the medical practices associated with BRCA risk, Pender's analysis shows that genetic risk is not just something BRCA+ women know, but also something that they do. It is through this doing that genetic cancer risk becomes a reality in their lives, one that we can explain but not one that we can explain away.Well researched and thoughtfully argued, Being at Genetic Risk will be welcomed by scholars of rhetoric and communication, particularly those who work in the rhetoric of science, technology, and medicine, as well as scholars in allied fields who study the social, ethical, and political implications of genetic medicine. Pender's insight will also be of interest to organizations that advocate for those at genetic risk of breast and ovarian cancers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAlchemyvEarly works to 1800. 0aAstrologyvEarly works to 1800. 0aMagicvEarly works to 1800. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Rhetoric.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311074522140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780271083025zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271083025423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271083025.jpg  a978-3-11-074522-1  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK